definition.value: A dodecatetraenedioic acid with double bonds at positions 2, 4, 8, and 10 (all E isomer).
The simplest diazo compound, in which a diazo group is attached to a methylene group.
A  alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is a C12 acid having four double bonds at unspecified positions in the chain.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is undecane substituted by carboxylic acid groups at positions C-1 and C-11.
A tridecadienoic acid with double bonds at positions 3 and 5 (both E isomer).
Any C14 polyunsaturated fatty aldehyde containing two double bonds.
A tetradecadienal with double bonds at positions 5 and 8.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,14-dicarboxy derivative of tetradecane.
A fatty acid derivative that is the 9Z-octadecenoyl derivative of glycine. It is believed to be an intermediate in oleamide biosynthesis.
A fatty amide obtained by the formal condensation of (11Z)-eicosaenoic acid with ethanolamine.

An aromatic ether that is phenoxyacetic acid in which the phenyl group is substituted at position 2 by a methyl group and at position 4 by a (1,3-thiazol-5-ylmethyl)sulfanediyl group, and in which the 1,3-thiazolyl group is substituted at positions 2 and 4 by p-trifluoromethylphenyl and methyl groups, respectively.

An organoammonium salt obtained by reaction of gadoteric acid with one equivalent of 1-deoxy-1-(methylamino)-D-glucitol (meglumine). It is used in magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) in brain (intracranial), spine and associated tissues of patients ages 2 years and older, to detect and visualise areas with disruption of the blood brain barrier and/or abnormal vascularity of the central nervous system.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,18-dicarboxy derivative of octadecane.
A PPAR modulator which activates the peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor-beta/delta.
An icosadienoic acid with double bonds at positions 11 and 14 (both Z).

A gadolinium coordination entity consisting of DOTA in which the four amino groups are bound to a central gadolinium atom. It is used (as its meglumine salt) in magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) in brain (intracranial), spine and associated tissues of patients ages 2 years and older, to detect and visualise areas with disruption of the blood brain barrier and/or abnormal vascularity of the central nervous system.
A fatty amide obtained by the formal condensation of (11Z,14Z)-eicosadienoic acid with ethanolamine.
Any C23 monounsaturated fatty acid containing one double bond at an unspecified position.
A tetracarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of gadoteric acid.
A tricosenoic acid having a double bond at position 22.
An  enynal  that is nonenal with a double bond at position 2 and triple bonds at positions 4, 6, and 8.
An alpha-amino fatty acid that is heptanoic acid substituted by an amino group at position 2 (the 2R stereoisomer).
A beta-amino acid that is caprylic acid which is substituted by an amino group at position 3.
A omega-amino fatty acid that is nonanoic acid substituted by an amino group at position 9.
A member of the class of prostaglandins Falpha that is the  dimethylamine derivative of prostaglandin F2alpha.
A dioxo monocarboxylic acid that is caprylic acid with the two oxo groups at the 4- and 7-positions.
A zwitterionic group obtained by transfer of a proton from the amino to the carboxy group of 2-(3-amino-3-carboxypropyl)-L-histidine residue.
A zwitterionic group obtained by transfer of a proton from the amino to the carboxy group of 2-[3-carboxy-3-(methylamino)propyl]-L-histidine residue
A zwitterionic group obtained by transfer of a proton from the amino to the carboxy group of 2-[3-carboxy-3-(dimethylamino)propyl]-L-histidine residue.
An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from 2-[3-carboxylato-3-(trimethylammonio)propyl]-L-histidine.
The nucleoside residue formed from uridine with linkages at the 3' and 5' positions.
An organic cationic group obtained by protonation of the exocyclic amino group of 5-aminomethyl-2-thiouridine residue.
A polyketide that is depudecin with a methyl hydrogen substituted with a hydroxy group.
Any C18 polyunsaturated fatty acid containing one C=C and two C#C bonds at unspecified positions.
An octadecenediynoic acid that is stearic acid with a cis double bond at position 13, two triple bonds at positions 9 and 11, and a hydroxy group at C-8.
A monohydroxy fatty acid that is heptanoic acid with a hydroxy group substituted at position C-2.
A monohydroxy fatty acid that is nonanoic acid with a hydroxy group substituted at position C-2.
A carbohydrate derivative in which one or more of the oxygens or hydroxy groups of the parent carbohydrate is replaced by sulfur or -SR, where R can be hydrogen or any group.

A member of the class of hydrazines that is hydrazine in which one of the hydrogens attached to each nitrogen is replaced by a methyl group. A powerful DNA alkylating agent and carcinogen, it is used to induce colon cancer in laboratory rats and mice.
A lipid hydroperoxide that consists of 2,3-dioxabicyclo[2.2.1]heptane substituted by a 11-methoxy-11-oxoundec-1-en-1-yl and a 3-hydroperoxypent-1-en-1-yl groups at positions 5 and 6 respectively.
A dipeptide formed from L-alanyl and glycine residues.
A  clavulone that is a chlorinated prostanoid isolated from marine corals.
A hydrochloride resulting from the reaction of 1,2,dimethylhydrazine with 2 mol eq. of hydrogen chloride.
An organic cation resulting from the protonation of both of the nitrogens of 1,2-dimethylhydrazine.
A dipeptide formed from L-alanyl and L-threonine residues.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of protons from the amino to the carboxy groups of 2-[3-carboxy-3-(dimethylamino)propyl]-L-histidine.
A L-histidine derivative that is L-histidine substituted at poisition 2 (on the imidazole ring) by a 3-carboxy-3-(dimethylamino)propyl group.
A trihydroxyoctadecenoic acid metabolite of linoleic acid formed by formal hydroxylation across one of the double bonds of hydroperoxyoctadecadienoic acids (HPODEs).
A L-histidine derivative that is L-histidine substituted at poisition 2 (on the imidazole ring) by a 3-carboxylato-3-(trimethylammonio)propyl group.
The nucleoside residue formed from 5-aminomethyl-2-thiouridine with linkages at the 3' and 5' positions.
